00:00:52.560 --> 00:00:54.610 align:middle line:90%
Is Mars dead?

00:00:54.610 --> 00:00:57.170 align:middle line:90%
And if so, do we care?

00:00:57.170 --> 00:01:00.350 align:middle line:84%
Dr. Brandenburg and
Monica Rix Paxson,

00:01:00.350 --> 00:01:04.580 align:middle line:84%
authors of "Dead Mars, Dying
Earth" say we'd better,

00:01:04.580 --> 00:01:08.870 align:middle line:84%
we are well on our way to
Earth meeting the same fate.

00:01:08.870 --> 00:01:12.860 align:middle line:84%
What does Mars have
to do with us, John?

00:01:12.860 --> 00:01:17.630 align:middle line:84%
>> Mars is an exhibit of
how this planet could end up

00:01:17.630 --> 00:01:21.530 align:middle line:84%
in the future if we don't
take better care of it.

00:01:21.530 --> 00:01:23.480 align:middle line:84%
Mars apparently
was a planet that

00:01:23.480 --> 00:01:26.330 align:middle line:84%
had a thriving
biosphere in the past.

00:01:26.330 --> 00:01:28.500 align:middle line:84%
We don't know the extent
of that biosphere.

00:01:28.500 --> 00:01:31.070 align:middle line:84%
We don't know how
far it advanced.

00:01:31.070 --> 00:01:35.870 align:middle line:84%
We do know, however, that the
present conditions on Mars

00:01:35.870 --> 00:01:40.370 align:middle line:84%
mean that only a small shadow
of that former biosphere

00:01:40.370 --> 00:01:42.050 align:middle line:90%
can exist on Mars now.

00:01:42.050 --> 00:01:45.020 align:middle line:84%
It appears a large
asteroid struck it.

00:01:45.020 --> 00:01:48.730 align:middle line:84%
>> We know Mars once had an
ocean that was larger than

00:01:48.730 --> 00:01:51.760 align:middle line:84%
the Pacific, and it
once had an atmosphere,

00:01:51.760 --> 00:01:54.730 align:middle line:84%
and it once had life,
and they're all gone.

00:01:54.730 --> 00:01:57.640 align:middle line:84%
And this is our nearest neighbor
so it's an important lesson

00:01:57.640 --> 00:01:58.960 align:middle line:90%
for our own planet.

00:01:58.960 --> 00:02:01.690 align:middle line:84%
>> Now, people are very
fascinated with the idea

00:02:01.690 --> 00:02:04.120 align:middle line:90%
of life on other planets.

00:02:04.120 --> 00:02:09.940 align:middle line:84%
Do you think that we are pretty
proud in saying that we are

00:02:09.940 --> 00:02:12.190 align:middle line:90%
the only life in the universe?

00:02:12.190 --> 00:02:13.720 align:middle line:90%
Do you think there is life?

00:02:13.720 --> 00:02:18.010 align:middle line:84%
>> I'm convinced that there is
life elsewhere in the universe.

00:02:18.010 --> 00:02:22.060 align:middle line:84%
To me, the Earth is a very
typical place in the universe.

00:02:22.060 --> 00:02:24.550 align:middle line:84%
We are very lucky
to be here, though.

00:02:24.550 --> 00:02:27.340 align:middle line:84%
It's a place where life
can thrive, and in fact,

00:02:27.340 --> 00:02:30.550 align:middle line:84%
shapes the environment,
particularly our oxygen

00:02:30.550 --> 00:02:34.690 align:middle line:84%
in the atmosphere,
the ozone layer.

00:02:34.690 --> 00:02:37.600 align:middle line:84%
So that we would expect it
elsewhere in the universe,

00:02:37.600 --> 00:02:39.040 align:middle line:90%
we would find similar planets.

00:02:39.040 --> 00:02:41.820 align:middle line:84%
Mars may have, in fact,
been a similar planet

00:02:41.820 --> 00:02:42.940 align:middle line:90%
to this one in the past.

00:02:42.940 --> 00:02:45.685 align:middle line:84%
>> Which planet do you
think might have life on it?

00:02:45.685 --> 00:02:48.470 align:middle line:84%
>> Oh, I think there is
certainly life on Mars now.

00:02:48.470 --> 00:02:49.270 align:middle line:90%
>> Now?

00:02:49.270 --> 00:02:52.070 align:middle line:84%
>> Just the infamous
primitive bacteria--

00:02:52.070 --> 00:02:52.870 align:middle line:90%
>> Really?

00:02:52.870 --> 00:02:55.270 align:middle line:84%
>> --that could survive
under the harsh conditions.

00:02:55.270 --> 00:02:58.270 align:middle line:84%
They find life in
places they thought

00:02:58.270 --> 00:03:00.010 align:middle line:84%
were impossible
for things to live

00:03:00.010 --> 00:03:02.380 align:middle line:84%
on Earth, miles
below the surface,

00:03:02.380 --> 00:03:04.900 align:middle line:84%
in the center of
nuclear reactors,

00:03:04.900 --> 00:03:08.530 align:middle line:84%
in places, deserts in
Antarctica that resemble Mars.

00:03:08.530 --> 00:03:09.910 align:middle line:90%
So I think there will be--

00:03:09.910 --> 00:03:12.970 align:middle line:84%
they will find that there is
bacterial life on Mars now.

00:03:12.970 --> 00:03:14.950 align:middle line:84%
>> But that doesn't
impress people.

00:03:14.950 --> 00:03:17.950 align:middle line:84%
Bacterial life, what about
people walking around?

00:03:17.950 --> 00:03:21.685 align:middle line:84%
What about these UFO people that
come-- the little blue people?

00:03:21.685 --> 00:03:26.620 align:middle line:84%
>> Well, we really are beginning
to look at what the history

00:03:26.620 --> 00:03:27.610 align:middle line:90%
of Mars is.

00:03:27.610 --> 00:03:32.420 align:middle line:84%
And it may have included
intelligent life of some sort.

00:03:32.420 --> 00:03:36.460 align:middle line:84%
It's certainly had a similar
history to the Earth.

00:03:36.460 --> 00:03:40.630 align:middle line:84%
It was a warm, wet planet,
life could have evolved there.

00:03:40.630 --> 00:03:44.410 align:middle line:84%
And we see some evidence of
some very interesting things

00:03:44.410 --> 00:03:47.950 align:middle line:84%
on Mars, things that we
wouldn't have expected to see,

00:03:47.950 --> 00:03:51.490 align:middle line:84%
things that look very
geometric, that looked fairly

00:03:51.490 --> 00:03:52.795 align:middle line:90%
sculptural or architectural.

00:03:52.795 --> 00:03:53.740 align:middle line:90%
>> Pyramids?

00:03:53.740 --> 00:03:55.540 align:middle line:90%
>> And pyramids, for example.

00:03:55.540 --> 00:03:59.890 align:middle line:84%
And we feel that it's an
important place for us

00:03:59.890 --> 00:04:04.150 align:middle line:84%
to continue to explore
and it is an open question

00:04:04.150 --> 00:04:09.835 align:middle line:84%
as to how long life was on
Mars and how evolved it became.

00:04:09.835 --> 00:04:12.435 align:middle line:84%
>> So what do you think
happened to Mars that killed it?

00:04:12.435 --> 00:04:14.680 align:middle line:84%
>> It appears a large
asteroid hit it.

00:04:14.680 --> 00:04:20.320 align:middle line:84%
We presented a hypothesis at
several scientific conventions

00:04:20.320 --> 00:04:24.880 align:middle line:84%
on the idea of an unstable
greenhouse on Mars

00:04:24.880 --> 00:04:26.740 align:middle line:90%
creating Earth-like conditions.

00:04:26.740 --> 00:04:30.820 align:middle line:84%
Mars needed a greenhouse to
have Earth-like conditions.

00:04:30.820 --> 00:04:33.010 align:middle line:84%
However, Carl Sagan
was the first one

00:04:33.010 --> 00:04:34.810 align:middle line:84%
to find out that such
a greenhouse would

00:04:34.810 --> 00:04:38.980 align:middle line:84%
have been unstable to like a
large asteroid striking Mars.

00:04:38.980 --> 00:04:40.450 align:middle line:84%
That would collapse
the greenhouse.

00:04:40.450 --> 00:04:42.790 align:middle line:84%
The greenhouse gas,
carbon dioxide,

00:04:42.790 --> 00:04:45.610 align:middle line:84%
would freeze out in the
dry ice on the surface.

00:04:45.610 --> 00:04:48.250 align:middle line:84%
The greenhouse would collapse
and not be able to recover.

00:04:48.250 --> 00:04:50.590 align:middle line:84%
>> Well, that's how we lost
our dinosaurs, isn't it?

00:04:50.590 --> 00:04:50.845 align:middle line:90%
Probably?

00:04:50.845 --> 00:04:51.100 align:middle line:90%
>> Exactly.

00:04:51.100 --> 00:04:52.225 align:middle line:90%
>> According to the theory.

00:04:52.225 --> 00:04:53.470 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah, it was very similar.

00:04:53.470 --> 00:04:56.380 align:middle line:84%
Here on this planet,
we were struck

00:04:56.380 --> 00:05:01.030 align:middle line:84%
by an asteroid or a
meteorite in the Chicxulub

00:05:01.030 --> 00:05:04.000 align:middle line:84%
region of the Yucatan
65 million years ago.

00:05:04.000 --> 00:05:09.010 align:middle line:84%
And it did, it reduced life
greatly on this planet.

00:05:09.010 --> 00:05:12.460 align:middle line:10%
We were a large enough planet
and close enough to the Sun

00:05:12.460 --> 00:05:14.410 align:middle line:10%
that we eventually recovered.

00:05:14.410 --> 00:05:15.285 align:middle line:10%
Mars did not.

00:05:15.285 --> 00:05:16.990 align:middle line:90%
>> Is Mars smaller than we are?

00:05:16.990 --> 00:05:18.320 align:middle line:90%
>> About half the size.

00:05:18.320 --> 00:05:19.810 align:middle line:90%
>> Half the size.

00:05:19.810 --> 00:05:24.140 align:middle line:84%
So that if a very
big asteroid hit us,

00:05:24.140 --> 00:05:26.185 align:middle line:84%
we could have the
same thing happen?

00:05:26.185 --> 00:05:28.300 align:middle line:90%
>> Yes.

00:05:28.300 --> 00:05:30.790 align:middle line:84%
Something the size that
wiped out the dinosaurs,

00:05:30.790 --> 00:05:36.720 align:middle line:84%
if it struck the planet again,
would certainly cause damage

00:05:36.720 --> 00:05:39.780 align:middle line:84%
that we would not be able
to recover from for probably

00:05:39.780 --> 00:05:40.920 align:middle line:90%
a million years.

00:05:40.920 --> 00:05:43.187 align:middle line:84%
Humanity might
disappear, unless steps

00:05:43.187 --> 00:05:44.270 align:middle line:90%
are taken to prevent that.

00:05:44.270 --> 00:05:46.290 align:middle line:90%
>> These are important risks.

00:05:46.290 --> 00:05:48.660 align:middle line:84%
But you know, we don't
even need a meteorite

00:05:48.660 --> 00:05:51.060 align:middle line:90%
to cause problems here on Earth.

00:05:51.060 --> 00:05:53.040 align:middle line:84%
>> We're doing it
ourselves, right?

00:05:53.040 --> 00:05:56.610 align:middle line:84%
>> We are actually generating
some of the same kinds

00:05:56.610 --> 00:06:00.900 align:middle line:84%
of effects that you might have
from that kind of strike with

00:06:00.900 --> 00:06:05.640 align:middle line:84%
our own use of fossil fuels
and increasing greenhouse gases

00:06:05.640 --> 00:06:07.260 align:middle line:90%
in our own atmosphere.

00:06:07.260 --> 00:06:10.830 align:middle line:84%
So we have a problem
and the problem

00:06:10.830 --> 00:06:13.290 align:middle line:84%
is we don't have to wait
to be hit by something

00:06:13.290 --> 00:06:14.280 align:middle line:90%
to have a problem.

00:06:14.280 --> 00:06:16.200 align:middle line:84%
We have a problem
now and we're seeing

00:06:16.200 --> 00:06:19.867 align:middle line:84%
some of the results of that
problem just even today.

00:06:19.867 --> 00:06:22.200 align:middle line:84%
>> Now, one of the points you
made in your book that was

00:06:22.200 --> 00:06:25.420 align:middle line:84%
interesting to me was
that our atmosphere,

00:06:25.420 --> 00:06:29.820 align:middle line:84%
which is being destroyed
by the carbon monoxide that

00:06:29.820 --> 00:06:34.500 align:middle line:84%
we're generating actually
keeps the asteroids away

00:06:34.500 --> 00:06:35.333 align:middle line:90%
and the comets away.

00:06:35.333 --> 00:06:36.133 align:middle line:90%
>> Yes.

00:06:36.133 --> 00:06:37.050 align:middle line:90%
>> I never knew that.

00:06:37.050 --> 00:06:40.850 align:middle line:84%
>> It functions kind of as a
bullet proof vest for a lot

00:06:40.850 --> 00:06:41.650 align:middle line:90%
of debris.

00:06:41.650 --> 00:06:42.450 align:middle line:90%
>> It deflects it?

00:06:42.450 --> 00:06:45.810 align:middle line:84%
>> Yes, it deflects it or
burns up the smaller pieces.

00:06:45.810 --> 00:06:48.270 align:middle line:10%
Eventually, though, one is
large enough and it gets through

00:06:48.270 --> 00:06:49.350 align:middle line:10%
and we've had--

00:06:49.350 --> 00:06:53.230 align:middle line:10%
we have the big meteorite
crater in Arizona.

00:06:53.230 --> 00:06:56.460 align:middle line:10%
We have the Tunguska
Event in Siberia,

00:06:56.460 --> 00:06:59.700 align:middle line:10%
and several more
recent near misses

00:06:59.700 --> 00:07:02.060 align:middle line:10%
that show that this
could happen at any time.

00:07:02.060 --> 00:07:04.420 align:middle line:84%
>> So the people who are
sitting back and saying, "Well,

00:07:04.420 --> 00:07:06.330 align:middle line:84%
I'm not going to worry
about this stuff.

00:07:06.330 --> 00:07:09.870 align:middle line:84%
That's going to happen two
million years from now."

00:07:09.870 --> 00:07:13.920 align:middle line:84%
The very fact that we're
destroying this layer leaves us

00:07:13.920 --> 00:07:17.670 align:middle line:84%
open for something that we
cannot possibly defend against,

00:07:17.670 --> 00:07:19.740 align:middle line:90%
a meteorite or a comet fittings.

00:07:19.740 --> 00:07:22.500 align:middle line:84%
>> What we're doing to the
Earth makes it more vulnerable

00:07:22.500 --> 00:07:24.300 align:middle line:90%
to the damage that would--

00:07:24.300 --> 00:07:26.430 align:middle line:84%
these things would pile
up on top of each other.

00:07:26.430 --> 00:07:32.460 align:middle line:84%
>> You know, it's also a
situation where we're evolving

00:07:32.460 --> 00:07:36.540 align:middle line:84%
as human beings and we will
continue to evolve provided we

00:07:36.540 --> 00:07:37.890 align:middle line:90%
survive.

00:07:37.890 --> 00:07:41.610 align:middle line:84%
And we have become space-fearing
people and citizens

00:07:41.610 --> 00:07:43.500 align:middle line:90%
of the cosmos, really.

00:07:43.500 --> 00:07:47.730 align:middle line:84%
And when you become citizens
of the cosmos, a citizen

00:07:47.730 --> 00:07:50.955 align:middle line:84%
of the cosmos, you suddenly
are responsible for your home

00:07:50.955 --> 00:07:54.580 align:middle line:84%
world in a way that you've
never perhaps been before.

00:07:54.580 --> 00:07:57.150 align:middle line:84%
So suddenly, we have
to prepare and be

00:07:57.150 --> 00:08:02.700 align:middle line:84%
aware of our atmosphere, our
oceans, and potential things

00:08:02.700 --> 00:08:04.980 align:middle line:84%
that might strike
us from outside.

00:08:04.980 --> 00:08:07.570 align:middle line:84%
>> There's a word that
everybody talks about.

00:08:07.570 --> 00:08:10.740 align:middle line:84%
And I'd like you to explain
exactly what it means--

00:08:10.740 --> 00:08:12.030 align:middle line:90%
global warming.

00:08:12.030 --> 00:08:15.575 align:middle line:84%
Let's start from A,
what is global warming?

00:08:15.575 --> 00:08:22.920 align:middle line:84%
>> Global warming is the
build-up of CO2 and other gases

00:08:22.920 --> 00:08:25.200 align:middle line:84%
that tend to trap
infrared radiation

00:08:25.200 --> 00:08:28.530 align:middle line:84%
in the Earth's atmosphere,
above levels that they have been

00:08:28.530 --> 00:08:30.930 align:middle line:90%
historically.

00:08:30.930 --> 00:08:34.230 align:middle line:84%
Some of this may be some natural
trend that we don't understand,

00:08:34.230 --> 00:08:37.825 align:middle line:84%
but however, the dominant effect
for raising the carbon dioxide

00:08:37.825 --> 00:08:39.450 align:middle line:84%
level in the Earth's
atmosphere appears

00:08:39.450 --> 00:08:42.840 align:middle line:84%
to be human use of fossil
fuels, which gives us

00:08:42.840 --> 00:08:49.110 align:middle line:84%
our civilization, our cars, our
televisions, our electricity.

00:08:49.110 --> 00:08:51.360 align:middle line:84%
So this build-up
of carbon dioxide

00:08:51.360 --> 00:08:56.970 align:middle line:84%
is changing the way the Earth's
environment accepts and rejects

00:08:56.970 --> 00:08:58.050 align:middle line:90%
heat.

00:08:58.050 --> 00:09:01.050 align:middle line:84%
We have the example of Venus
in our own solar system that

00:09:01.050 --> 00:09:04.140 align:middle line:84%
has an overwhelming greenhouse,
and the temperatures

00:09:04.140 --> 00:09:07.620 align:middle line:84%
on the surface of Venus are
close to the melting point

00:09:07.620 --> 00:09:08.910 align:middle line:90%
of lead.

00:09:08.910 --> 00:09:12.870 align:middle line:10%
It's absolutely a hellish
place, and it's much hotter

00:09:12.870 --> 00:09:16.290 align:middle line:10%
than it would be if
it had no atmosphere.

00:09:16.290 --> 00:09:18.810 align:middle line:10%
Then, of course,
we have the Earth

00:09:18.810 --> 00:09:22.230 align:middle line:10%
and we're raising
the level of carbon

00:09:22.230 --> 00:09:26.970 align:middle line:10%
dioxide in the atmosphere so
that it will trap more heat.

00:09:26.970 --> 00:09:30.620 align:middle line:84%
One of the methods of using
carbon dioxide in industrial

00:09:30.620 --> 00:09:34.140 align:middle line:84%
use to make CO2 lasers,
these are infrared lasers.

00:09:34.140 --> 00:09:35.130 align:middle line:90%
They're very powerful.

00:09:35.130 --> 00:09:38.180 align:middle line:84%
They're used for cutting
thick pieces of steel.

00:09:38.180 --> 00:09:42.030 align:middle line:84%
Infrared radiation and carbon
dioxide love each other.

00:09:42.030 --> 00:09:45.470 align:middle line:84%
And when you raise that, change
that level in the Earth's

00:09:45.470 --> 00:09:48.500 align:middle line:84%
atmosphere, you affect
how it processes heat,

00:09:48.500 --> 00:09:52.340 align:middle line:84%
just like changing the
thermostat on your house

00:09:52.340 --> 00:09:53.240 align:middle line:90%
and your living room.

00:09:53.240 --> 00:09:57.050 align:middle line:84%
>> So coming back to it,
let's talk about the Midwest

00:09:57.050 --> 00:10:01.190 align:middle line:84%
of Chicago because we're taping
this in Chicago, Midwest area.

00:10:01.190 --> 00:10:05.910 align:middle line:84%
We had in February, almost
80-degree weather here.

00:10:05.910 --> 00:10:07.780 align:middle line:84%
Well, and two
summers ago, we had

00:10:07.780 --> 00:10:12.180 align:middle line:90%
heat of 121 degrees Fahrenheit.

00:10:12.180 --> 00:10:15.360 align:middle line:84%
Is this because of
this global warming?

00:10:15.360 --> 00:10:17.232 align:middle line:90%
Is this what causing it?

00:10:17.232 --> 00:10:20.360 align:middle line:84%
>> I hate to say it, but global
warming is not going to mean

00:10:20.360 --> 00:10:23.510 align:middle line:84%
just a gradual raising
of temperatures.

00:10:23.510 --> 00:10:25.505 align:middle line:84%
It's going to be
killer heat waves.

00:10:25.505 --> 00:10:28.970 align:middle line:84%
>> Wait a minute, this is really
serious and we want to hear

00:10:28.970 --> 00:10:30.630 align:middle line:90%
more about this.

